Stochastic learning

Consider a predictive rule \(h:\mathbb{R}\rightarrow \mathbb{R}\) with

\[ h\left(x\right)=w_{0}+w_{1}x \]

and \(x\in\mathbb{R}\).

Assume that there is a training data set

\[ \mathcal{S}_{n}=\left\{ z_{i}=\left(x_{i},y_{i}\right)\right\} _{i=1}^{n} \]

with \(n=100\).

Run the following R script to obtain the training data set \(\mathcal{S}_{n}\) as a data frame object with name training.data.1 .

githubURL <-"https://github.com/georgios-stats/Machine_Learning_and_Neural_Networks_III_Epiphany_2023/raw/main/Exercises/misc/Homework_4/training.data.1.Rda"
load(url(githubURL))

You will notice that training.data.1 contains two self-explained variables training.data.1\(x and training.data.1\)y.

Consider a loss function

\[ \ell\left(w,z=\left(x,y\right)\right)=\left|y-w_{0}-w_{1}x_{1}\right| \]

and hence Empirical Risk Function

\[ \hat{R}_{n}\left(w\right)=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\ell\left(w,z_{i}=\left(x_{i},y_{i}\right)\right) \]

Question

To learn \(w\), code a gradient descent learning algorithm that aims to minimize the Empirical Risk Function under the above loss function and the provided training data set \(\mathcal{S}_{n}\).

Your gradient descent algorithm should converge to an optimal value in no more than 50 iterations.

Use any value in the range \((-3,3)\times (-3,3)\) for the seed \(w^{(0)}\).

Use a constant learning rate \(\eta_{t}\). You have to adjust the value of the learning rate \(\eta_{t}\), so that your algorithm can achieve convergence in no more than 50 iterations.

Write down the R code.

loss_fun <- function(w,z) {
  x <- z[1]
  y <- z[2]
  loss_fun <- abs( y -w[1] - w[2]*x )
}
#
empirical_risk_fun <- function(w,z,n) {
  erf <- 0.0
  for (i in 1:n) {
    x <- z[i,1]
    y <- z[i,2]
    erf <- erf + abs( y -w[1] - w[2]*x )  
  }
  erf <- erf/n
  return( erf )
}
#
training.data.1
z_obs <- as.matrix(training.data.1)
n_obs <- dim(z_obs)[1]
#
#
eta <- 0.5
Tmax <- 50
w_seed <- c(-0,0)
w <- w_seed
w_chain <- c()
Qstop <- 0 
t <- 0
while ( Qstop == 0 ) {
  # counter
  t <- t +  1
  cat( t ) ; cat( ' ' ) ## counter added for display reasons
  # step 1: update  
  erf_fun <- function(w, z = z_obs, n=n_obs) {
    return( empirical_risk_fun(w, z, n) ) 
  }
  w <- w - eta * numDeriv::grad( erf_fun, w )
  w_chain <- rbind(w_chain, w)
  # step 2: check for termination terminate
  if ( t>= Tmax ) {
    Qstop <- 1
  }
}

w_opt <- w_chain[1,]
erf_opt <- empirical_risk_fun(w_opt,z_obs,n_obs)
for (i in 2:Tmax) {
  w_now <- w_chain[i,]
  erf_now <- empirical_risk_fun(w_now,z_obs,n_obs)

Consider another training data set with size \(n=100000\).

Assume that your computer cannot process the gradient descent you created above to learn algorithm with the new training data set. In particular, due to your limited computer resources, assume that your computer is able to compute the Empirical Risk Function over \(n=10\) (or less) examples (from the training data set).

In a principle manner, modify your gradient descent learning algorithm in order to to address the aforesaid limited resources problem and learn the unknown ws given the available training data set.

Properly, adjust the parameters of your modified algorithm so that it can converge around the optimal values of ws in less than 100 iterations.

Use any value in the range \((-3,3)\times (-3,3)\) for the seed \(w^{(0)}\).

Copy your modified code below.

Justify why you modified your code that way, and why this is a suitable implementation of the algorithm for the given problem.

# I will implement SGD with batch size m=10 because it stochastically chooses sub-samples smaller than the total sample size, hence the problem of the limited resources is addressed. Because the examples are stochastically chosen after several iterations I could have possibly (and eventually) scan all the availabel training data set.    

loss_fun <- function(w,z) {
  x <- z[1]
  y <- z[2]
  loss_fun <- abs( y -w[1] - w[2]*x )
}
#
empirical_risk_fun <- function(w,z,n) {
  erf <- 0.0
  for (i in 1:n) {
    x <- z[i,1]
    y <- z[i,2]
    erf <- erf + abs( y -w[1] - w[2]*x )  
  }
  erf <- erf/n
  return( erf )
}
#
training.data.2 
z_obs <- as.matrix(training.data.2)
n_obs <- dim(z_obs)[1]
#
#
m <- 10
eta <- 0.8
Tmax <- 100
w_seed <- c(-3,3)
w <- w_seed
w_chain <- c()
Qstop <- 0 
t <- 0
while ( Qstop == 0 ) {
  # counter
  t <- t +  1
  cat( t ) ; cat( ' ' ) ## counter added for display reasons
  # step 1: update  
  J <- sample.int(n = n_obs, size = m, replace = TRUE)
  if (m==1) {
    zbatch <- matrix(z_obs[J,],1,2)
  }
  else {
    zbatch <- z_obs[J,]
  }
  #eta <- learning_rate( t )
  erf_fun <- function(w, z = zbatch, n=m) {
    return( empirical_risk_fun(w, z, n) ) 
  }
  w <- w - eta * numDeriv::grad( erf_fun, w )
  w_chain <- rbind(w_chain, w)
  # step 2: check for rtermination terminate
  if ( t>= Tmax ) {
    Qstop <- 1
  }
}

The following application is about using chemical analysis to determine the origin of wines.

You can download the training data set by using the following command

githubURL <-"https://github.com/georgios-stats/Machine_Learning_and_Neural_Networks_III_Epiphany_2023/raw/main/Exercises/misc/Homework_4/train.data.3.Rda"
load(url(githubURL))

You can download the evaluation data set by using the following command

githubURL <-"https://github.com/georgios-stats/Machine_Learning_and_Neural_Networks_III_Epiphany_2023/raw/main/Exercises/misc/Homework_4/valid.data.3.Rda"
load(url(githubURL))

The data under consideration are the results of a chemical analysis of wines grown in the same region in Italy but derived from three different cultivars. The analysis determined the quantities of 12 constituents found in each of the three types of wines.

Names of variables:

V1) Origin of the wine (1: Region 1 ; 2: Region 2; 3: Region 3) V3) Malic acid V4) Ash V7) Total phenols V8) Flavanoids V9) Nonflavanoid phenols V10) Proanthocyanins V11 Color intensity V12 Hue V13 OD280/OD315 of diluted wines

Question

By using suitable R packages, train a neural network with one hidden layer that consists of 10 hidden unites with purpose to train a classifier that is able to classify a wine to the correct region.

Consider decay equal to 0.001.

The performance measure is the match metric namely

\[ \text{match}=\frac{1}{n_{\text{eval}}}\sum_{i=1}^{n_{\text{eval}}}\text{1}\left(y_{i}^{\text{true}}=y_{i}^{\text{predicted}}\right) \]

where \(n_{eval}\) is the size of the evaluation data set, \(y_{i}^{\text{true}}\) is the true class, and \(y_{i}^{\text{predicted}}\) is the predicted class of i-th case.

Your trained Neural Network should be such that it can achieve at least a 95% match when compared to the validation data set.

Write down the code.

Report your achieved match.

where \(C\) is the cost parameter.
